Styling Text and Fonts in CSS

CSS provides a rich set of properties to style text and fonts on web pages. Here are some of the most commonly used properties:

Font Properties:

.font-family: Specifies the font family to use for the text.
.font-size: Sets the size of the font.
.font-weight: Defines the weight or boldness of the font.
.font-style: Sets the font style, such as italic or oblique.

Text Properties:

.text-align: Aligns the text within its container (left, right, center, justify).
.text-decoration: Adds decorations to the text, such as underline or strikethrough.
.text-transform: Changes the case of the text (uppercase, lowercase, capitalize).
.color: Sets the color of the text.
Example HTML and CSS:

HTML:

HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Text and Font Styling</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Heading 1</h1>
    <h2>Heading 2</h2>
    <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>
    <a href="https://example.com">Link to Example Website</a>
</body>
</html>


CSS:

CSS
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    font-size: 16px;
}

h1 {
    font-size: 36px;
    font-weight: bold;
    text-align: center;
}

h2 {
    font-size: 24px;
    font-weight: bold;
}

p {
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.5;
}

a {
    color: blue;
    text-decoration: none;
}

a:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
}